<p>
Hewlett-Packard (HP) CEO <a href="http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9220224/What_will_Whitman_bring_to_HP_">Meg Whitman</a> said last week that the company has reached the halfway point in its restructuring, with 15,000 employees left to cut to meet its layoff target.
</p>
<p>
HP last May announced plans to <a href="http://www.pcworld.com/article/256092/hp_to_trim_27000_jobs_as_part_of_restructuring_program.html?tk=rel_news">reduce its workforce by some 27,000 people</a> out of a staff of 350,000. The company is using layoffs and early retirement incentives to reach its goal by the end of next year.
</p>
<figure class="right original"><img src="http://images.techhive.com/images/article/2013/02/meg-whitman-hp-100026437-orig.jpg" height="275" width="200" alt="Meg Whitman HP CEO"/><figcaption>Meg Whitman</figcaption></figure><p>
